# Metric Resource: LevenshteinDistance
<https://w3id.org/cq4oe/metric/LevenshteinDistance> a dqv:Metric ;

    dcterms:identifier "https://w3id.org/cq4oe/metric/LevenshteinDistance" ;
    dcterms:title "Character-level edit distance approximation"@en ;
    rdfs:label "LevenshteinDistance: Character-level edit distance approximation"^^xsd:string ;
    vivo:abbreviation "levenshtein"^^xsd:string ;
    dcat:version "0.0.1"^^xsd:string ;
    ftr:status "Active"@en ;
    dcat:landingPage <https://w3id.org/cq4oe/metric/LevenshteinDistance> ;

    # Descriptive Content
    dcterms:description """
This metric computes the normalized Levenshtein similarity between a generated label and each gold-standard label, returning a score in [0, 1]. The Levenshtein distance counts the minimum number of single-character insertions, deletions, or substitutions needed to transform one string into another.

**Calculation Process:**

1. Compute the Levenshtein edit distance d(generated, gold).
2. Normalize: similarity = 1 - d / max(len(generated), len(gold)).
3. Take the maximum similarity across all gold labels.
4. A pair is considered a match if the score is greater than or equal to 0.8 (default lexical threshold).

**Example:**

Generate_Label: HasColor

Gold_Standard_Label: HasColour

LevenshteinDistance(Generate_Label, Gold_Standard_Label) = 0.89

**What is being measured?**

This metric tolerates small character-level edits anywhere in the string. It is more forgiving than HardMatch but cares only about characters, not meaning.
""" ;
    dcat:keyword "Ontology Concept Matching"@en ;
    dcat:keyword "Metric"@en ;
    dcat:keyword "Classes"@en ;

    # Relationships and Provenance
    dpv:isApplicableFor <https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q184754> ;
    ftr:hasBenchmark <https://w3id.org/cq2onto/benchmark/ALL> ;
    sio:SIO_000234 <https://w3id.org/cq4oe/metric/LevenshteinDistance> ;
    ftr:supportedBy <https://w3id.org/cq2onto/> ;
    dqv:inDimension "Ontology Engineering"^^xsd:string ;

